        "# Conclusion & Recommendations\n",
        "\n",
        "## Summary of the Work\n",
        "In this case study we built a complete movie Recommender System for Zee using collaborative filtering. We merged the ratings, users and movies files into one dataframe, performed EDA and feature engineering (decoded Age & Occupation, derived Release Year and Decade), and then implemented four recommendation approaches: Item-based Pearson Correlation, Item-based Cosine Similarity with KNN, Matrix Factorization (SVD) with latent embeddings, and an optional User-based Pearson approach for new users.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Key Insights from EDA\n",
        "- The most active raters belong to the 25-34 age group, and college/grad students are the most active profession, so the platform's core audience is young and educated.\n",
        "- The majority of raters are Male, indicating a gender imbalance that the recommendation strategy and content acquisition should keep in mind.\n",
        "- Most movies in the catalogue were released in the 1990s decade, and 'American Beauty (1999)' has the highest number of ratings, making it a strong anchor title for popularity-based fallbacks.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Model Performance\n",
        "The Matrix Factorization (SVD, d=4) model achieved an RMSE of about 0.88 and a MAPE of about 27% on the held-out test set. This is a solid result and clearly outperforms a naive popularity baseline, showing that latent factors capture genuine user taste patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Recommendations for Zee\n",
        "1. **Use Matrix Factorization (SVD) as the primary engine.** It gave the lowest error, scales well to a sparse 6040 x 3952 matrix, and produces compact d-dimensional embeddings that can be reused for both rating prediction and similarity search.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Combine models in a hybrid setup.** Use item-based Cosine/Pearson similarity for the \"Because you watched X\" rows and SVD for the personalized \"Top picks for you\" row. This gives users both intuitive and personalized recommendations.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Solve the cold-start problem with the User-based approach.** For brand-new users with no history, ask them to rate 5-10 popular movies (as demonstrated) and recommend based on the most similar existing users. Fall back to popularity-based recommendations (e.g. American Beauty, Star Wars) when no data is available.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **Filter by minimum rating count.** Recommendations should ignore movies with very few ratings (we used a threshold of 50-100) to avoid unreliable similarity scores driven by noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "5. **Address the demographic skew.** Since the audience skews young, male and toward 1990s titles, Zee should monitor whether recommendations reinforce this bias and consider promoting diverse and recent content to broaden engagement.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Future Improvements\n",
        "Performance could be improved further by tuning the number of latent factors, adding implicit signals (watch time, clicks), incorporating content-based features (genre, cast, release year) into a hybrid model, and periodically retraining the model as new ratings arrive to keep recommendations fresh."
      ],
